04494nam a22005535i 9780822398424DE-B159720210225050953.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210225t20122005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223984247 a10.1515/97808223984242doi  a(DE-B1597)552195  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS3604.I48bK79 2005 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a813/.62221 aDinin, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Krzyzewskiville Tales /cAaron Dinin. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b20 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tGeneral prologue -- tThe captain -- tThe engineer -- tThe sociology major -- tThe public policy major -- tThe freshman -- tThe economics major -- tAn interruption to the storytelling competition -- tAaron -- tThe women's studies major -- tThe pre-med student -- tThe math major's tale -- tThe pre-law student -- tThe english major -- tGeneral epilogue -- tCrazie talk0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent Duke University graduate Aaron Dinin has produced an entertaining, imaginative look at Krzyzewskiville, the tent city named after Duke University's head men's basketball coach Mike Krzyzewski (Sha-shef-ski). A unique Duke tradition, Krzyzewskiville is used to determine which students are admitted into key games. Taking Geoffrey Chaucer's Canterbury Tales as his model, Dinin has created characters who narrate their semifictionalized tales-by turns reverent, bawdy, and humorous-to enlighten readers about this cherished institution.So the story begins. On a wintry night in Durham, North Carolina, writes Dinin, twelve students huddle under the meager protection of a nylon tent. They have little in common except the sacrosanct tradition that has brought them together for the past month. Before the sun next sets, they will anoint themselves in blue and white paint and enter nearby Cameron Indoor Stadium to worship at the altar of Blue Devils basketball. In the meantime, they abide in Krzyzewskiville.A stranger enters the tent, a respected sportswriter, and suggests that the tenters pass the hours until the next tent check by telling stories of Krzyzewskiville. Like Chaucer's pilgrims, the students compete to tell the best tale. They report on ribald tenting exploits, relate a dream in which Duke basketball players and coaches test a fan's loyalty, debate the rationality of tenting as a way of allocating students' tickets, and describe the spontaneous tent city that sprang up one summer when their beloved "Coach K" was offered a job elsewhere. This storytelling competition creates a loving portrait of the complex rules and tribal customs that make up the rich community and loyal fans that are Krzyzewskiville.Mickie Krzyzewski, Coach K's wife and a familiar courtside figure at Duke basketball games, has contributed a foreword praising the "love, commitment, and ownership" of the citizens of Krzyzewskiville.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aBasketball fansvFiction. 0aCampingvFiction. 0aCollege sportsvFiction. 0aCollege studentsvFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822398424zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822398424423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822398424.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles